we risk saying that even in fiction,

251
00:11:03,534 --> 00:11:05,996
some types of characters necessarily have limitations

252
00:11:05,996 --> 00:11:07,276
that others don't.

253
00:11:07,276 --> 00:11:09,657
And for me, the thing that made Cersei's decision

254
00:11:09,657 --> 00:11:12,278
so interesting was the fact that she had no choice

255
00:11:12,278 --> 00:11:15,720
but to make them alongside, around, and even using men.

256
00:11:15,720 --> 00:11:18,521
As everyone in the story loves to point out to her,

257
00:11:18,521 --> 00:11:19,742
Cersei is not the queen.

258
00:11:19,742 --> 00:11:22,843
She's the king's wife, and even the king's mother.

259
00:11:22,843 --> 00:11:24,444
And from that indirect role, she had

260
00:11:24,444 --> 00:11:27,105
to be so much cleverer and more of a survivor

261
00:11:27,105 --> 00:11:29,927
than she would have been if she had just

262
00:11:29,927 --> 00:11:31,087
been a regular old monarch.

263
00:11:31,758 --> 00:11:34,739
Let's move on to Beyonce, the great queen.

264
00:11:34,739 --> 00:11:36,720
Actually, this slide is not, unfortunately,

265
00:11:36,720 --> 00:11:37,620
is not about Beyonce.

266
00:11:37,620 --> 00:11:41,362
I just thought you'd rather see her than Cersei.

267
00:11:41,362 --> 00:11:43,323
As I was saying, I wanted the Reigns queen

268
00:11:43,323 --> 00:11:46,865
to have the same range of grotesque, silly, thirsty,

269
00:11:46,865 --> 00:11:50,426
ruthless, vain, loving choices for the player

270
00:11:50,426 --> 00:11:53,347
as the Reigns king did, without uncritically celebrating

271
00:11:53,347 --> 00:11:54,268
traditional power.

272
00:11:54,268 --> 00:11:55,488
And in a way that I thought.

273
00:11:55,795 --> 00:12:01,278
could really let me kind of tap into that tireless manipulative agility of a character like Cersei.

274
00:12:01,278 --> 00:12:05,640
So I thought, let's shift the locus of power in the game just a little bit for Her Majesty.

275
00:12:05,640 --> 00:12:10,142
You're the queen, but like Cersei, you're not on the throne, you're the king's wife.

276
00:12:10,142 --> 00:12:13,004
You'd like to have the same kind of power and freedom as the king,

277
00:12:13,004 --> 00:12:16,946
but you're surrounded by sabotage, incompetence, double standards,

278
00:12:16,946 --> 00:12:21,068
men who are half as qualified as you, yet receive twice as much respect.

279
00:12:21,556 --> 00:12:25,803
I wanted the player to feel at times like the only voice of reason in a despairing kingdom

280
00:12:25,803 --> 00:12:30,751
of fools because that's an interesting kind of power that is difficult for women to assert.

281
00:12:31,887 --> 00:12:34,209
So as I was saying, I came up with this whole political

282
00:12:34,209 --> 00:12:36,550
rationale for why you play as the king's wife instead of as

283
00:12:36,550 --> 00:12:37,351
a woman ruler.

284
00:12:37,351 --> 00:12:41,014
But the larger reason for this decision was mainly to enable

285
00:12:41,014 --> 00:12:43,176
some of the kinds of narrative beats that I wanted to write.

286
00:12:43,176 --> 00:12:45,878
You know, a ruler has to make decisions about whether to

287
00:12:45,878 --> 00:12:47,259
build a dam or not.

288
00:12:47,259 --> 00:12:50,562
A lot of the reign's king's decisions were stat management

289
00:12:50,562 --> 00:12:51,202
of the land.

290
00:12:51,202 --> 00:12:53,985
But really, I was kind of more attracted to the idea of

291
00:12:53,985 --> 00:12:56,667
managing the kingdom via social intrigue and sideways

292
00:12:56,667 --> 00:12:58,648
influence and making moves behind the scenes.

293
00:12:59,137 --> 00:13:01,418
Now, that is not to say, oh, men fight with swords

294
00:13:01,418 --> 00:13:03,999
and women use words and feelings.

295
00:13:03,999 --> 00:13:06,700
You know, any time I have been interested in simply

296
00:13:06,700 --> 00:13:09,961
new mechanics that are perhaps more story-driven and slightly

297
00:13:09,961 --> 00:13:12,122
less concerned with violence or conventional power,

298
00:13:12,122 --> 00:13:13,843
people are like, oh, so just talking,

299
00:13:13,843 --> 00:13:15,564
solving problems by talking.

300
00:13:15,564 --> 00:13:17,985
Because men fight and women talk, supposedly.

301
00:13:17,985 --> 00:13:20,706
And that stark conclusion that people jump to, for me,

302
00:13:20,706 --> 00:13:21,867
miscarries the point.

303
00:13:21,867 --> 00:13:24,328
When you don't have access to conventional power,

304
00:13:24,328 --> 00:13:26,589
you have to make more complicated and more personal

305
00:13:26,589 --> 00:13:27,569
choices in conflict.

306
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:32,062
It's sometimes more interesting when you don't have as much control as you want.

307
00:13:32,062 --> 00:13:36,604
So let's say in Reigns, Her Majesty, if you find the life of a king's wife and a church

308
00:13:36,604 --> 00:13:40,346
figurehead demeaning and confining, and you probably will, you have to shake things up

309
00:13:40,346 --> 00:13:45,048
through unconventional means, you know, dark bargains, ambiguous righteousness, self-service,

310
00:13:45,048 --> 00:13:49,090
using people who trust you, all while making sure you're viewed as lovable and powerful

311
00:13:49,090 --> 00:13:50,691
and fun in the acceptable way.

312
00:13:51,153 --> 00:13:53,374
Those kinds of dynamics are conflict.

313
00:13:53,374 --> 00:13:55,935
They are full of violence, conflict, and cruelty,

314
00:13:55,935 --> 00:13:57,255
and tough choices, and messiness.

315
00:13:57,255 --> 00:14:00,756
And I think we do those types of mechanics a disservice

316
00:14:00,756 --> 00:14:03,437
when we reduce them to, oh, just talking it out.

317
00:14:03,437 --> 00:14:05,438
Also, that being said, we did use poetry

318
00:14:05,438 --> 00:14:06,679
for our dual mechanics.

319
00:14:06,679 --> 00:14:08,299
The team thought that would be fun.

320
00:14:08,299 --> 00:14:11,140
So these ideas about the narrative

321
00:14:11,140 --> 00:14:13,961
emerged for me most of all not from outside influences,

322
00:14:13,961 --> 00:14:15,902
but from the native systems themselves.

323
00:14:16,495 --> 00:14:18,016
This concept that's innate to Reigns,

324
00:14:18,016 --> 00:14:20,398
that you're constantly trying to please

325
00:14:20,398 --> 00:14:22,119
multiple irreconcilable goods,

326
00:14:22,119 --> 00:14:23,820
you can't always say what you'd really like

327
00:14:23,820 --> 00:14:26,002
because you can't statistically afford it,

328
00:14:26,002 --> 00:14:28,144
takes lifetimes to eke out progress,

329
00:14:28,144 --> 00:14:30,806
that just felt like a pretty natural field

330
00:14:30,806 --> 00:14:32,647
in which to stage an experience

331
00:14:32,647 --> 00:14:34,148
about being a woman trying to gain

332
00:14:34,148 --> 00:14:35,789
any kind of power for herself,

333
00:14:35,789 --> 00:14:37,451
no matter what your definition of power is.

334
00:14:38,672 --> 00:14:42,294
So the original Reign's dynamic, where people were constantly coming to you with needs,

335
00:14:42,294 --> 00:14:45,415
was, as you can imagine, pretty fruitful to work with.

336
00:14:45,415 --> 00:14:49,496
And I saw a great opportunity to build a non-linear narrative experience

337
00:14:49,496 --> 00:14:53,518
of just those thousands of moments where your objectives and your desires,

338
00:14:53,518 --> 00:14:56,339
whether for yourself or your kingdom, naturally conflict.

339
00:14:56,339 --> 00:15:00,681
I thought maybe Reign's Her Majesty could go a little further than the first game

340
00:15:00,681 --> 00:15:04,442
just in terms of an interactive fiction experience, which is my personal favorite genre.

341
00:15:05,041 --> 00:15:08,744
I thought that deepening our storytelling could invite and entertain players who were

342
00:15:08,744 --> 00:15:12,847
not necessarily systems thinkers and that even those who didn't want to dig into the

343
00:15:12,847 --> 00:15:16,650
item quests and the mysteries and the hardcore bits, because some Reigns fans are very hardcore

344
00:15:16,650 --> 00:15:20,814
so we had to account for them, but other people I wanted to also just have a lot of fun telling

345
00:15:20,814 --> 00:15:23,816
the stories of all these different queens and seeing the possibilities.

346
00:15:23,816 --> 00:15:29,180
Now before I dig a little deeper I'm not going to spend a huge amount of time on the technical

347
00:15:29,180 --> 00:15:33,764
bits because we need to focus on the pure white hot advocacy that I'm beaming out into

348
00:15:33,764 --> 00:15:34,104
this room.

349
00:15:35,317 --> 00:15:39,179
But people do ask me all the time how I approach writing these modular stories.

350
00:15:39,179 --> 00:15:43,522
And by modular, I mean the way that individual and even unrelated cards hopefully tend to

351
00:15:43,522 --> 00:15:46,804
always coalesce somewhat into miniature arcs for each reign.

352
00:15:46,804 --> 00:15:51,547
The answer to that is really, it's as much about how we balanced it as it was about how

353
00:15:51,547 --> 00:15:52,728
I wrote it.

354
00:15:52,728 --> 00:15:57,230
So real quick, I wrote individual cards, had to create the moment within the length of

355
00:15:57,230 --> 00:16:01,713
a tweet, and each card had to offer diametric expressive choices, as well as clue the player

356
00:16:01,713 --> 00:16:03,374
about the potential effect of those choices.

357
00:16:03,908 --> 00:16:06,772
And then I had to decide the result of those choices.

358
00:16:06,772 --> 00:16:08,874
So every card has a weight, a probability

359
00:16:08,874 --> 00:16:10,737
which determines how likely it is to appear.

360
00:16:11,120 --> 00:16:13,561
I suggested the statistical impacts of choices,

361
00:16:13,561 --> 00:16:16,263
as well as link them up to other cards that could appear

362
00:16:16,263 --> 00:16:18,123
as certain consequences later.

363
00:16:18,123 --> 00:16:20,564
So in addition to just having writing at my disposal

364
00:16:20,564 --> 00:16:22,225
as a utility, I could also decide

365
00:16:22,225 --> 00:16:24,386
how this network of probabilities performed.

366
00:16:24,386 --> 00:16:27,227
The words you read are only half of the narrative experience.

367
00:16:27,227 --> 00:16:31,309
It's also about how it feels and behaves, how it's paced.

368
00:16:31,309 --> 00:16:33,950
And luckily, I had expressive tools at my disposal,

369
00:16:33,950 --> 00:16:36,131
the system that Francois Alliot created,

370
00:16:36,131 --> 00:16:37,412
which he used to make rains.

371
00:16:37,412 --> 00:16:38,532
This is where I wrote the game.

372
00:16:38,532 --> 00:16:39,553
It's in Google Sheets.

373
00:16:41,110 --> 00:16:43,452
Not sure how well you can see it, but as you can see,

374
00:16:43,452 --> 00:16:45,714
we have the ability to designate the bearer

375
00:16:45,714 --> 00:16:48,116
who appears on the card, what the questions they ask,

376
00:16:48,116 --> 00:16:50,918
conditions that are relevant to the card's appearance,

377
00:16:50,918 --> 00:16:53,020
statistical effects, and then other outcomes,

378
00:16:53,020 --> 00:16:55,282
like let's say a certain decision adds something

379
00:16:55,282 --> 00:16:57,964
to the deck or sets a new permanent condition.

380
00:16:57,964 --> 00:16:59,525
People have asked, oh, you should make

381
00:16:59,525 --> 00:17:01,627
a Reigns card game with physical cards,

382
00:17:01,627 --> 00:17:04,229
but hopefully this illustrates that that would probably,

383
00:17:04,229 --> 00:17:06,731
in my view, be difficult, because it's not the cards,

384
00:17:06,731 --> 00:17:08,753
it's the system in which the cards are performing.

385
00:17:09,244 --> 00:17:14,187
So I could essentially use these numbers as well as words as tools to construct the story.

386
00:17:14,187 --> 00:17:18,649
The statistical impact of something you do in the game gives you narrative information.

387
00:17:18,649 --> 00:17:23,211
To use a heavy-handed example, let's say in this world there's a contentious relationship

388
00:17:23,211 --> 00:17:25,832
between the church and practitioners of magic.

389
00:17:25,832 --> 00:17:30,215
And that could be communicated numerically by watching the numbers on the church decline

390
00:17:30,215 --> 00:17:32,836
when you do something that feels magical or feels rebellious.

391
00:17:32,836 --> 00:17:38,078
So even though that was a statistical assignation, it was something I could use for narrative expression.

392
00:17:39,039 --> 00:17:43,980
As a team, Francois had to do a lot of balancing for me because I count on my fingers.

393
00:17:43,980 --> 00:17:49,062
So we did a lot of adjustments as a team to balance the game and make sure it felt the

394
00:17:49,062 --> 00:17:52,102
way it was supposed to feel, the gating was working properly.

395
00:17:52,102 --> 00:17:56,743
Hopefully everyone's experience is different, every rain is different, there's a progression

396
00:17:56,743 --> 00:17:58,044
but every rain is still different.

397
00:17:58,044 --> 00:18:03,525
There are hopefully lots of harmonious and happy accidents and hopefully it becomes transparent

398
00:18:03,525 --> 00:18:06,786
enough that you feel a sense of direction but not so much that it's predictable.

399
00:18:07,923 --> 00:18:11,365
Ultimately, I liken it to doing knitting in a spreadsheet,

400
00:18:11,365 --> 00:18:12,885
starting with moments and conflicts

401
00:18:12,885 --> 00:18:14,026
that I wanted the player to feel

402
00:18:14,026 --> 00:18:15,446
and then making them link up,

403
00:18:15,446 --> 00:18:17,788
reference one another and loop back.

404
00:18:17,788 --> 00:18:20,449
In a way, it was a lot like an IF authoring tool

405
00:18:20,449 --> 00:18:23,190
because all the great ones used the language of weaving,

406
00:18:23,190 --> 00:18:25,911
like a knot or a skein or a thread, a twine, you know.

407
00:18:25,911 --> 00:18:28,713
So great, we have this system

408
00:18:28,713 --> 00:18:30,633
that can very effectively make you feel.

409
00:18:30,963 --> 00:18:34,067
put upon, disempowered, and overwhelmed by choices.

410
00:18:34,067 --> 00:18:36,950
And that inspired me to make a game about how hard it

411
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:38,672
is to be taken seriously as a woman,

412
00:18:38,672 --> 00:18:40,674
so that anyone who picks this up gets the chance

413
00:18:40,674 --> 00:18:42,135
to experience that.

414
00:18:42,135 --> 00:18:45,659
Get me my Feminist Advocate Award, right?

415
00:18:45,659 --> 00:18:49,023
So although I have always been a great believer

416
00:18:49,023 --> 00:18:50,945
in the strength of interactive environments

417
00:18:50,945 --> 00:18:52,487
to help shift people's perspectives.

418
00:18:52,726 --> 00:18:57,209
Thanks to the great critical writings and games of designers like Robert Yang and Anthropy,

419
00:18:57,209 --> 00:19:01,512
I've come to strongly believe that simply reproducing an oppressive system so that others

420
00:19:01,512 --> 00:19:06,175
can experience how horrible it is, is not a sufficiently constructive way to approach

421
00:19:06,175 --> 00:19:06,635
our work.

422
00:19:06,635 --> 00:19:11,198
I think the options that we give players for how to consider or act on those experiences

423
00:19:11,198 --> 00:19:12,279
are much more important.

424
00:19:12,279 --> 00:19:18,062
So even though I was conscious of the expectations that Reign's Her Majesty should at least be

425
00:19:18,062 --> 00:19:20,904
trying its best to be a feminist work, and I'll get back to that in a bit.

426
00:19:21,262 --> 00:19:25,604
The social challenges that the Queen faces are hopefully only a catalyst for a broader

427
00:19:25,604 --> 00:19:27,304
and more ambiguous dialogue.

428
00:19:27,304 --> 00:19:29,065
Again, the system is horrible, we get it.

429
00:19:29,065 --> 00:19:33,768
Anguished portrayals of how bad it is for women or people of color or otherwise marginalized

430
00:19:33,768 --> 00:19:36,589
individuals make white guys feel like they're being enlightened.

431
00:19:36,589 --> 00:19:41,131
But for the rest of us on our end, I think we're all much more interested in how folks

432
00:19:41,131 --> 00:19:45,293
